## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### What breaks and why

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` â€” it no longer works at all. Your code has **four** APIs that must be replaced:

| API | Location | Issue |
|-----|----------|-------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` / SYSLIB0006 |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | `ProcessLoop()` | Never thrown â€” cleanup logic silently skipped |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `volatile bool _running` | field | Works but insufficient â€” can't interrupt blocking calls |

### Patterns identified

1. **Cancellable work loop** â€” `while (_running)` â†’ use `CancellationToken`
2. **ThreadAbortException as control flow** â€” catch block does rollback â†’ `catch (OperationCanceledException)`
3. **ResetAbort to continue** â€” keeps thread alive after abort â†’ check `IsCancellationRequested` instead
4. **Blocking call interruption** â€” `GetNextItem()` blocks and `Abort()` was the only way to break out â†’ pass token into the blocking call

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested â€” clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit naturally.
                // If you want to continue processing remaining items instead of
                // exiting, just `continue` here (but typically you want to stop).
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation â€” replaces Thread.Abort

        // Join with timeout replaces Thread.Sleep + IsAlive check
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't stop in time. With cooperative cancellation,
                // this means GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't responding to the
                // token. Log a warning â€” you cannot force-kill it in modern .NET.
                Console.WriteLine("Warning: worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical: update `GetNextItem` to accept the token

The **biggest pitfall** â€” if `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), cancellation will stall there because cooperative cancellation only works if the blocking call checks the token. You must pass it through:

```csharp
// BEFORE â€” blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection<T>.Take()
}

// AFTER â€” wakes up immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If your blocking call doesn't accept a token (e.g., raw `Socket.Receive`), replace it with an async overload or poll with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(timeout)`.

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing token to blocking calls** | `_cts.Cancel()` does nothing if `GetNextItem()` is stuck in an uninterruptible block. The thread hangs forever. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always wrap in `IDisposable` or `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish cancellation from other `OperationCanceledException` sources. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It's cooperative â€” there's latency between `Cancel()` and the next checkpoint. `Join(timeout)` handles this. |
| **Removing cleanup without migrating it** | Your `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` was in the `ThreadAbortException` catch â€” don't lose it. It's now in the `OperationCanceledException` catch. |
